<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
Aromatic annuals or, rarely, perennial herbs and small subshrubs covered with glandular hairs, subsessile yellow or orange glands and simple white hairs. Leaves alternate, entire, lobate or pinnatisect. Inflorescence lax or dense, leafy or not, consisting of cymes that are often reduced to one flower only. Perianth segments 2-5, free or variously connate, the midrib usually with keel. Stamens 1-5. Styles 2, free or basally connate. Fruit subglobose or rarely flattened, 0.3-1.5 mm, its surface reticulate or papillate, rarely smooth, dark coloured but often with whitish longitudinal stripes. Pericarp adjoining the seed coat, rarely bursting, hyaline, consisting of 1-2 very thin layers. Seed reddish or reddish-black, sometimes brown, its testa (outer seed coat layer) lacking vertical tannin-like deposits called 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“stalactites”">&quot;stalactites&quot;</normalizedToken>
in cross-section. Embryo horizontal or vertical, sometimes in both positions within one plant (spatial heterospermy).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
More than 50 species worldwide, mostly in the tropics and subtropics. According to the first comprehensive molecular phylogeny (Kadereit et al. in prep.), the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown, Fl. Nov. Holland.: 411" authorityYear="1810" class="Insecta" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Dysphania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dysphania" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Dysphania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is monophyletic and there is no reason to accept the genera 
<taxonomicName authority="Moldenke, 1946" authorityName="Moldenke" authorityYear="1946" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chenopodiacea" genus="Neobotrydium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Neobotrydium" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Neobotrydium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authority="Moq., 1840" authorityName="Moq." authorityYear="1840" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chenopodiacea" genus="Ambrina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ambrina" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Ambrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as was recently proposed (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pld.2016.10.005" author="Zhang, M" journalOrPublisher="Plant Diversity" pageId="132" pageNumber="133" pagination="322 - 329" refId="B134" refString="Zhang, M, Zhu, GL, 2016. Resurrection of the genus Botrydium Spach (Chenopodiaceae), with a description of four new species from China, Peru and Burundi. Plant Diversity 38 (6): 322 - 329, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pld.2016.10.005" title="Resurrection of the genus Botrydium Spach (Chenopodiaceae), with a description of four new species from China, Peru and Burundi." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pld.2016.10.005" volume="38" year="2016">Zhang and Zhu 2016</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhu, GL" journalOrPublisher="Ulmaceae-Basellaceae. Science Press, Beijing, and Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis" pageId="132" pageNumber="133" refId="B138" refString="Zhu, GL, Sanderson, SC, 2017. Genera and a new evolutionary system of World Chenopodiaceae. Science Press, Beijing." title="Genera and a new evolutionary system of World Chenopodiaceae. Science Press, Beijing." year="2017">Zhu and Sanderson 2017</bibRefCitation>
). All native species are closely related and belong to a large clade consisting of Eurasian and African representatives. The mountainous areas of Himalaya and Tibet are now considered one of the four centres of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown, Fl. Nov. Holland.: 411" authorityYear="1810" class="Insecta" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Dysphania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dysphania" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Dysphania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
diversity, together with Australia, South America and East Tropical Africa (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.191.1.2" author="Sukhorukov, AP" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="130" pageNumber="131" pagination="10 - 44" refId="B108" refString="Sukhorukov, AP, Kushunina, MA, 2014. Taxonomic revision of Chenopodiaceae in Nepal. Phytotaxa 191 (1): 10 - 44, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.191.1.2" title="Taxonomic revision of Chenopodiaceae in Nepal." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.191.1.2" volume="191" year="2014">Sukhorukov and Kushunina 2014</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5091/plecevo.2016.1181" author="Sukhorukov, AP" journalOrPublisher="Plant Ecology and Evolution" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" pagination="249 - 256" refId="B116" refString="Sukhorukov, AP, Kushunina, MA, Verloove, F, 2016a. Notes on Atriplex, Oxybasis and Dysphania (Chenopodiaceae) in West-Central Tropical Africa. Plant Ecology and Evolution 149 (2): 249 - 256, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5091/plecevo.2016.1181" title="Notes on Atriplex, Oxybasis and Dysphania (Chenopodiaceae) in West-Central Tropical Africa." url="https://doi.org/10.5091/plecevo.2016.1181" volume="149" year="2016 a">Sukhorukov et al. 2016a</bibRefCitation>
). The evident structural fruit and seed dimorphism in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown, Fl. Nov. Holland.: 411" authorityYear="1810" class="Insecta" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Dysphania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dysphania" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Dysphania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chenopodiaceae" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. tibetica" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="tibetica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">D. tibetica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is stated here for the first time.
</paragraph>
